HLD – FR160

SDN Support for Arrcus ArcOS Installation based on ONIE

---

1. Overview

This document describes the high-level design for supporting automated Arrcus ArcOS installation on ONIE-compatible network switches through the SDN NOS Management framework.

The solution enables:

- automated ArcOS image onboarding
- ONIE-based installer discovery
- centralized image staging
- installation orchestration
- installation status verification

The workflow supports both:

- physical ONIE-compatible switches
- virtual ArcOS qcow2 instances

---

2. Objective

The objective of this FR is to automate ArcOS installation on supported network devices using ONIE installer workflows and centralized orchestration through the SDN platform.

The SDN system should:

- stage ArcOS installer artifacts
- expose installer metadata through DHCP
- trigger ONIE-based installation
- monitor installation progress
- verify successful ArcOS boot

---

3. Scope

In Scope

- ONIE-based ArcOS installation workflow
- ArcOS installer image staging
- DHCP-based installer discovery
- Installation orchestration and monitoring
- Installation success verification
- Support for physical and virtual devices

Out of Scope

- Day-1 provisioning orchestration
- Runtime service provisioning
- ZTP ownership/workflow management
- Network configuration lifecycle management

Post-install provisioning remains handled by the existing provisioning framework.

---

4. High-Level Architecture

4.1 Components

4.1.1 nos-updator Service

Primary orchestration service responsible for:

- onboarding installation requests
- staging installer artifacts
- configuring installer metadata
- triggering installation workflow
- monitoring installation lifecycle
- reporting installation status

---

4.1.2 Staging HTTP Server

Hosts installation artifacts including:

- ArcOS installer image
- installation metadata
- checksum files

Supported protocols:

- HTTP
- HTTPS
- optional TFTP support

---

4.1.3 DHCP Server

Provides ONIE installer discovery information.

The DHCP server exposes:

- installer URL
- boot metadata

using DHCP Option 125.

---

4.1.4 ONIE-Compatible Switch

Target device where:

- ONIE performs installer discovery
- ArcOS image installation occurs
- system reboots into ArcOS

Supported targets:

- physical switches
- virtual qcow2-based ArcOS instances

---

5. Installation Workflow

Stage A – Installation Request

1. User/API triggers installation request
2. nos-updator validates request metadata
3. ArcOS installer image is staged on HTTP server
4. DHCP installer metadata is configured

---

Stage B – ONIE Discovery

1. Device powers ON
2. ONIE bootloader starts
3. ONIE sends DHCP discovery request
4. DHCP server returns:
   - installer URL
   - boot metadata

through DHCP Option 125.

---

Stage C – ArcOS Installation

1. ONIE downloads ArcOS installer image
2. ArcOS installation begins
3. Installer writes image to device storage
4. Device reboots after successful installation

---

Stage D – Installation Verification

1. ArcOS boots successfully
2. nos-updator verifies device reachability
3. Installed ArcOS version validated
4. Installation status marked successful

After successful ArcOS boot, the device transitions into the existing provisioning workflow managed outside the scope of this FR.

---

6. End-to-End Flow

Installation Request
        ↓
Artifact Staging
        ↓
DHCP Metadata Configuration
        ↓
ONIE Boot
        ↓
DHCP Discovery
        ↓
Receive Installer URL
        ↓
Download ArcOS Installer
        ↓
Install ArcOS
        ↓
Reboot
        ↓
ArcOS Boot
        ↓
Installation Verification
        ↓
Installation Success

---

7. Virtual ArcOS Support

Virtual ArcOS qcow2 instances already contain the ArcOS image.

For virtual devices:

- ONIE installation stage is skipped
- ArcOS boots directly
- installation verification flow remains applicable

Supported environments:

- KVM
- QEMU
- virtualization-based labs/testing

---

8. API Design

Endpoint

PUT /nosupdate

---

Request Parameters

Parameter| Description
deviceId| Target device identifier
vendor| Device vendor
model| Device model
macAddress| Device MAC address
nosImageUrl| ArcOS installer URL
nosVersion| Target ArcOS version

---

Response

Field| Description
requestId| Installation workflow ID
status| Workflow status
message| Operation result

---

9. DHCP Configuration

The DHCP server exposes installer discovery metadata for ONIE devices.

DHCP Option Usage

DHCP Option| Purpose
Option 125| ONIE installer URL

Example:

option onie.installer-url "http://staging-server/arcos-installer.bin";

---

10. Installation Verification

Installation is considered successful when:

- ArcOS boots successfully
- target version is reachable
- device responds through management interface

Verification methods:

- management IP reachability
- SSH verification
- version validation

---

11. Failure Handling

Failure Scenarios

- DHCP discovery failure
- installer download failure
- installation timeout
- reboot failure
- ArcOS boot failure

Recovery Handling

- retry installation
- timeout handling
- failure reporting
- rollback hooks for future enhancements

---

12. Security Considerations

- restricted access to staging server
- validated installer artifacts
- secure management access
- controlled installation workflows

---

13. Assumptions

- Device is ONIE compatible
- Management network connectivity exists
- DHCP server is reachable
- Installer artifacts are accessible
- Device supports ArcOS installation

---

14. Future Enhancements

- automated rollback support
- checksum/fingerprint validation
- parallel installation workflows
- provisioning integration hooks
- enhanced telemetry support

---

15. Summary

This design enables automated ArcOS installation on ONIE-compatible devices using centralized orchestration through the SDN NOS Management framework.

The solution provides:

- automated installer discovery
- centralized image staging
- scalable installation workflows
- installation monitoring
- support for both physical and virtual environments

while keeping post-install provisioning external to the scope of FR160.
